  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good books on marketing?",
  "response": "Here are some highly regarded books on marketing that cover a range of topics, from strategy and branding to digital marketing and consumer behavior:\n\n### Classic and Foundational:\n1. **\"Influence: The Psychology of Persuasion\" by Robert B. Cialdini**  \n   Explores the principles of persuasion and how they can be applied in marketing.\n\n2. **\"Positioning: The Battle for Your Mind\" by Al Ries and Jack Trout**  \n   A foundational book on how to position your brand in the minds of consumers.\n\n3. **\"The 22 Immutable Laws of Marketing\" by Al Ries and Jack Trout**  \n   Offers timeless principles for successful marketing strategies.\n\n4. **\"Contagious: How to Build Word of Mouth in the Digital Age\" by Jonah Berger**  \n   Explains why certain products and ideas go viral and how to harness this power.\n\n### Branding and Strategy:\n5. **\"Building a StoryBrand: Clarify Your Message So Customers Will Listen\" by Donald Miller**  \n   Focuses on crafting a clear and compelling brand story.\n\n6. **\"Good to Great: Why Some Companies Make the Leap... and Others Don't\" by Jim Collins**  \n   Explores what sets successful companies apart, with marketing implications.\n\n7. **\"Blue Ocean Strategy: How to Create Uncontested Market Space and Make the Competition Irrelevant\" by W. Chan Kim and Ren\u00e9e Mauborgne**  \n   Introduces strategies for creating new market demand rather than competing in crowded spaces.\n\n### Digital Marketing and Social Media:\n8. **\"Digital Marketing for Dummies\" by Ryan Deiss and Russ Henneberry**  \n   A comprehensive guide to digital marketing strategies and tools.\n\n9. **\"Epic Content Marketing: How to Tell a Different Story, Break Through the Clutter, and Win More Customers by Marketing Less\" by Joe Pulizzi**  \n   Focuses on creating valuable content that attracts and retains customers.\n\n10. **\"Jab, Jab, Jab, Right Hook: How to Tell Your Story in a Noisy Social World\" by Gary Vaynerchuk**  \n    Offers practical advice on using social media effectively.\n\n### Consumer Behavior and Insights:\n11. **\"Hooked: How to Build Habit-Forming Products\" by Nir Eyal**  \n    Explains how to create products that keep users engaged and coming back.\n\n12. **\"Thinking, Fast and Slow\" by Daniel Kahneman**  \n    While not strictly a marketing book, it provides deep insights into consumer decision-making.\n\n13. **\"Why We Buy: The Science of Shopping\" by Paco Underhill**  \n    A fascinating look into the psychology of shopping and retail environments.\n\n### Practical Guides and Case Studies:\n14. **\"Made to Stick: Why Some Ideas Survive and Others Die\" by Chip Heath and Dan Heath**  \n    Explains how to make ideas memorable and impactful.\n\n15. **\"Purple Cow: Transform Your Business by Being Remarkable\" by Seth Godin**  \n    Encourages businesses to stand out by being truly remarkable.\n\n16. **\"The Art of SEO: Mastering Search Engine Optimization\" by Eric Enge, Stephan Spencer, and Jessie Stricchiola**  \n    A comprehensive guide to SEO strategies.\n\n### Recent and Innovative:\n17. **\"This Is Marketing: You Can\u2019t Be Seen Until You Learn to See\" by Seth Godin**  \n    A modern take on marketing with a focus on empathy and storytelling.\n\n18. **\"Marketing 4.0: Moving from Traditional to Digital\" by Philip Kotler, Hermawan Kartajaya, and Iwan Setiawan**  \n    Explores the shift from traditional to digital marketing.\n\n19. **\"Subscribed: Why the Subscription Model Will Be Your Company's Future\u2014and What to Do About It\" by Tien Tzuo**  \n    Discusses the rise of subscription-based business models.\n\nThese books cover a wide spectrum of marketing topics, so you can choose based on your specific interests or needs. Whether you're a beginner or a seasoned professional, there's something here for everyone!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
